{"title_page": "Finn Carling", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Finn Carling\n| image         = Finn Carling.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Finn Carling in 1974\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1925|10|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Oslo]], Norway\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2004|3|12|1925|10|1|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Norwegian\n| other_names   = \n| spouse        = \n| parents       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| occupation    = Novelist, playwright, poet and essayist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| awards        = [[Riksm\u00e5l Society Literature Prize]] (1970)<br />[[Gyldendal's Endowment]] (1976)<br />[[Dobloug Prize]] (1986)<br />[[Aschehoug Prize]] (1987)<br />[[Arts Council Norway Honorary Award]] (1999)\n}}\n'''Finn Carling''' (1 October 1925 &ndash; 12 March 2004) was a [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] novelist, playwright, poet and essayist. \n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/wiki/Finn_Carling|title=Finn Carling|publisher =  lokalhistoriewiki|accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Oslo]], Norway.   He took [[artium]] in 1945 and studied psychology at the [[University of Oslo]] from 1945-49. He followed with a course of study of sociology, history and literature at [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] during 1957-58.\n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allkunne.no/framside/biografiar/c/finn-carling//86/9258/|title=Finn Carling|publisher =Allkunne     \n|date=  May 16, 2013|accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe made his literary debut in 1949 with ''Broen'' (two short stories and a one-act play). He had  authorship of several genres, and became a key figure in Norwegian post-war literature. Carling had innate [[cerebral palsy]]. He described his childhood and adolescence with this disability in the [[autobiographical novel]] ''Kilden og muren'' (1958).<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn Carling |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Hans H |last=Skei |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Finn_Carling/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn Carling |first1=Hans H |last1=Skei |first2=Morten |last2=Moi |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor-last=Godal | editor-first=Anne Marit | editor-link=Anne Marit Godal |publisher=Norsk nettleksikon |location=Oslo |url=http://snl.no/Finn_Carling |language=Norwegian | accessdate=2 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHe died during 2004 and was buried at  Voksen kirkeg\u00e5rd in Oslo.<ref name=kl>{{cite web |url=http://www.kulturrad.no/om_oss/aeresprisen/ |title=\u00c6resprisen  |publisher=Norsk Kulturr\u00e5d (Arts Council Norway) |date= |language=Norwegian |accessdate=2008-10-26}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*[[Riksm\u00e5l Society Literature Prize]] - 1970\n*[[Gyldendal's Endowment]] - 1976\n*[[Dobloug Prize]] - 1986\n*[[Aschehoug Prize]] - 1987\n*[[Norsk kulturr\u00e5ds \u00e6respris]] - 1999\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Other sources==\n*{{cite journal|jstor =40152043|title=Finn Carling: A Personal Introduction\n|publisher =  World Literature Today. Vol. 70, No. 2 (Spring, 1996), pp. 277-282|author=Louis Muinzer}} \n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Sverre Fehn]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Recipient of the [[Norsk kulturr\u00e5ds \u00e6respris]] | years = 1999 }}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Anne Brown]]}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[P\u00e5l Sundvor]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title =Recipient of the [[Gyldendal's Endowment]] | years = 1976 (shared with [[Sigurd Evensmo]]) }}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Jan Jakob T\u00f8nseth]] }}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Portal|Norway|Biography|Society|Art}}\n\n{{Dobloug Prize winners|state =collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carling, Finn}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Oslo]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male poets]]\n[[Category:Norwegian essayists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian male writers]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Dobloug Prize winners]]\n\n{{Norway-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Finn Carling\n| image         = Finn Carling.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Finn Carling in 1974\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1925|10|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Oslo]], Norway\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2004|3|12|1925|10|1|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Norwegian\n| other_names   = \n| spouse        = \n| parents       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| occupation    = Novelist, playwright, poet and essayist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| awards        = [[Riksm\u00e5l Society Literature Prize]] (1970)<br />[[Gyldendal's Endowment]] (1976)<br />[[Dobloug Prize]] (1986)<br />[[Aschehoug Prize]] (1987)<br />[[Arts Council Norway Honorary Award]] (1999)\n}}\n'''Finn Carling''' (1 October 1925 &ndash; 12 March 2004) was a [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]] novelist, playwright, poet and essayist. \n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/wiki/Finn_Carling|title=Finn Carling|publisher =  lokalhistoriewiki|accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Oslo]], Norway.   He took [[artium]] in 1945 and studied psychology at the [[University of Oslo]] from 1945-49. He followed with a course of study of sociology, history and literature at [[Howard University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] during 1957-58.\n<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.allkunne.no/framside/biografiar/c/finn-carling//86/9258/|title=Finn Carling|publisher =Allkunne     \n|date=  May 16, 2013|accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe made his literary debut in 1949 with ''Broen'' (two short stories and a one-act play). He had  authorship of several genres, and became a key figure in Norwegian post-war literature. Carling had innate [[cerebral palsy]]. He described his childhood and adolescence with this disability in the [[autobiographical novel]] ''Kilden og muren'' (1958).<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn Carling |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Hans H |last=Skei |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Finn_Carling/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Finn Carling |first1=Hans H |last1=Skei |first2=Morten |last2=Moi |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor-last=Godal | editor-first=Anne Marit | editor-link=Anne Marit Godal |publisher=Norsk nettleksikon |location=Oslo |url=http://snl.no/Finn_Carling |language=Norwegian | accessdate=2 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHe died during 2004 and was buried at  Voksen kirkeg\u00e5rd in Oslo.<ref name=kl>{{cite web |url=http://www.kulturrad.no/om_oss/aeresprisen/ |title=\u00c6resprisen  |publisher=Norsk Kulturr\u00e5d (Arts Council Norway) |date= |language=Norwegian |accessdate=2008-10-26}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*[[Riksm\u00e5l Society Literature Prize]] - 1970\n*[[Gyldendal's Endowment]] - 1976\n*[[Dobloug Prize]] - 1986\n*[[Aschehoug Prize]] - 1987\n*[[Norsk kulturr\u00e5ds \u00e6respris]] - 1999\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Other sources==\n*{{cite journal|jstor =40152043|title=Finn Carling: A Personal Introduction\n|publisher =  World Literature Today. Vol. 70, No. 2 (Spring, 1996), pp. 277-282|author=Louis Muinzer}} \n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Sverre Fehn]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = Recipient of the [[Norsk kulturr\u00e5ds \u00e6respris]]